apropos [keyword] to search manual!!


ps to show processes

find to find files, with many options

| used to redirect the output of a command to the input of another command
e.g. who|grep Yoyo, will find Yoyo in the output of who, instead of a file
e.g. ls *.py|sort will sort all .py files in the dir

> to redirect but will overwrite the file

>> to redirect but just add text

\ to split long command into several lines

TCP/IP tools:
nslookup traceroute netstat ping nbstat

sudo -i or sudo su      to switch to root

cat/less/more   three ways to view a file


--------------------
ls    in detail

     --cc      Use time when file status was last changed for sorting (--tt) or
             complete time information for the file, including month, day,
     --tt      Sort by time modified (most recently modified first) before sort-
     --uu      Use time of last access, instead of last modification of the file
     --UU      Use time of file creation, instead of last modification for sort-
     mines the file time used.
     If the modification time of the file is more than 6 months in the past or
     TZ              The timezone to use when displaying dates.  See
--------------------

nice    to execute a process in a altered priority

du    to view the situation of disk
df    to display the freedisk space

chdir can also change dir

limit to display resource limit    (ulimit)

syslog to display system log

 to suspend a job

jobs   to display suspended jobs

ps -e    will show all processes

kill [No] to kill a process

fg, bg  to continue a job in front/background
